<p>The fall of the Roman empire had nothing to do with resources, energy, environment, overpopulation or the rise of a mighty competitor. Nietzsche blamed the corrupting influence of Christianity for the decay of traditional Roman values: you can&#8217;t run an empire with pussies at the helm. In the end they ran out of Romans. Rome became a cosmopolitan cities with people from all corners of the empire, very &#8216;vibrant&#8217; no doubt but with little internal cohesion. Everybody was interested in entertainment, fighting not so much. </p>
<p>It took seven centuries for the Roman empire to reach it&#8217;s zenith and four to be terminated by a bunch of Germans. The American windfall empire came into being as a result of maneuvering others into war, with minimal fighting of itself and joining the battle when it was already almost over. For every dead American there were fifty dead Soviet allies. Most military operations against tiny opponents after 1945 ended in failure. The ambitions of the ruling Straussian elite are unlimited, but the aging Euro-American battlehorse is tired of wars and of the direction the country is heading: the third world. In the end the Americans won&#8217;t be beaten on their own turf by a bunch of Germans, Russians or Chinese, like the Romans were. The American dollar empire could go under after foreigners will pull the financial rug from under the Americans, after which parts of the American homeland will turn into a Bostonian pressure cooker and explode and the &#8216;diversity is your strength&#8217; meme pushed by the Straussians will turn into &#8216;diversity is your civil war&#8217;.</p>
<p>Don&#8217;t know how long the US empire will last. Certainly not two centuries. Two decades more likely, two years also possible if the BRICS dump the dollar.</p>
